Description: A biodegradable thermoplastic made from corn starch or sugarcane.
Notes: Ideal for 3D printing, packaging, and disposable cutlery.
Molecular_Notes: Lactic acid monomer (use repeat ester linkage for polymer).

Description: A biopolymer produced by bacterial fermentation of sugars and lipids.
Notes: Used for medical implants, packaging films, and agriculture mulch.

Description: A biodegradable polyester with low melting point and flexibility.
Notes: Used in drug delivery systems and biomedical applications.

Description: Derived from corn, potato, or cassava starch.
Notes: Great for compostable packaging and disposable food containers.

Description: A plant-derived thermoplastic from cellulose and acetic acid.
Notes: Used in eyeglass frames, filters, and films.

Description: Derived from chitin found in shellfish shells.
Notes: Used for water purification, wound dressings, and coatings.

Description: Protein-based biodegradable plastic from soybeans.
Notes: Suitable for films and adhesives.

Description: Milk protein-based thermoplastic.
Notes: Historically used in buttons, jewelry, and sustainable crafts.
Molecular_Notes: Representative small peptide fragment from casein proteins.

Description: Derived from collagen found in animal tissues.
Notes: Used in capsules, coatings, and edible films.

Description: Made from seaweed biomass with renewable sourcing.
Notes: Used in films, packaging, and biodegradable plastics.
Molecular_Notes: Representative small polyol/acid fragment from alginate-like polymers.

Description: Composite made from bamboo fibers and bio-resin.
Notes: Strong and lightweight — ideal for panels and furniture.

Description: Sustainable composite reinforced with hemp fibers.
Notes: Used in automotive parts, construction, and textiles.

Description: Composite material with flax fibers and biodegradable resin.
Notes: Used in sports goods, vehicles, and building panels.

Description: Plant-based fiber composite offering strength and biodegradability.
Notes: Used in packaging and furniture.

Description: Made from banana stem fibers with natural resins.
Notes: Used in biodegradable packaging and automotive panels.

Description: Coconut husk fiber reinforced with biodegradable resin.

Description: High-tensile plant fiber used in composites.

Description: Agricultural waste composite with bio-resins.

Description: Byproduct of sugarcane with good strength-to-weight ratio.

Description: Palm waste fiber mixed with biodegradable binders.

Description: Harvested from the bark of cork oak trees.

Molecular_Notes: Representative suberin-like phenolic fragment (cork is rich in suberin).

Description: Soft, lightweight wood from the balsa tree.
Notes: Used in model structures, insulation, and composites.

Description: Fast-growing renewable grass material.
Notes: Used in construction, flooring, and utensils.

Description: Natural bast fiber known for strength and flexibility.
Notes: Used in textiles, ropes, and biocomposites.

Description: Soft natural fiber from cotton plant.
Notes: Used for textiles, paper, and bioplastics.

Description: Natural protein fiber from silkworms.
Notes: Used for medical sutures, textiles, and films.
Molecular_Notes: Representative aromatic-containing peptide fragment for silk fibroin.

Description: Protein fiber from sheep or alpacas.

Description: Flax-based textile fiber.
Notes: Used in high-quality textiles and composites.

Description: Strong natural fiber from jute plants.
Notes: Used for bags, ropes, and bio-composites.

Description: Fiber from Chinese nettle plant.
Notes: Used for textiles and high-strength composites.

Description: Root-like fungal network grown into shapes.

Description: Produced by bacteria with high purity and strength.
Notes: Used for wound dressings, electronics, and composites.

Description: Extracted from brown seaweed.

Molecular_Notes: Representative alginic acid fragment (uronic acid dimer-like).

Description: Natural structural protein from connective tissue.
Notes: Used in biomedical scaffolds and films.
Molecular_Notes: Glycine-proline motif representative; collagen is long peptide.

Description: Protein from hair, wool, and feathers.
Notes: Used for bioplastics, films, and fertilizers.

Description: Polysaccharide from fruit peels.

Description: Derived from lignin, a byproduct of paper industry.

Molecular_Notes: Guaiacyl-type lignin fragment as representative aromatic unit.

Description: Fiber extracted from corn husks.

Description: Fibrous residue from sugarcane.

Description: Plant protein-based film.

Description: Reprocessed cellulose fibers.
Notes: Used for molded packaging and eco-friendly crafts.

Description: Compressed reused paper fibers.

Description: Eco-friendly variant of PU.

Description: Blend of two biopolymers for strength and flexibility.

Description: Modified starch turned into thermoplastic.
Notes: Used for films and disposable items.

Description: Elastic material from latex sap.
Notes: Used for tires, gloves, and sealants.

Description: Repurposed cotton fibers blended for reuse.

Description: Eco polyester derived from waste bioplastics.
Notes: Used in fabrics and durable packaging.

Description: Renewable resin alternative.
Notes: Used in coatings and bio-composites.

Description: Cotton fabric coated with beeswax.
